SSL and TLS Protocols:

SSL Protocol, operates in a layered structure with the SSL record protocol at the lowest level providing basic security services to higher SSL levels. Above the Record Protocol are the SSL Handshake Protocol and the SSL Change Cipher Spec Protocol. The SSL Handshake Protocol allows authentication and key exchange while the SSL Change Cipher Spec Protocol signals changes in encryption strategies. The highest level is the SSL Alert Protocol which is responsible for error reporting. SSL Protocol is comprised of three primary phases, establishing a secure connection, exchanging encrypted data, and closing the connection.

TSL Protocol, follows a similar process to SSL with enhancements to security and performance. It is also organized in a layered structure with the TLS Record Protocol at the base providing basic security services to higher TLS levels. The TLS Handshake Protocol and the TLS Change Cipher Spec Protocol sit above the Record Protocol with the TLS Alert Protocol at the highest level. TLS supports more advanced encryption algorithms and offers better protection against potential attacks. The primary difference between SSL  and TLS lies in the cryptographic algorithms and message formats.


