Identity Scope:

*Azure AAD is an Identity Access Management System (IAM) which means it is tasked with creating and profiling identity and the extent to which it can access a system. It does this through the use of roles. Within a business context, different roles or functions need to be executed like a manager, waiter, or accountant. The scope is the set of resources that access applies to.

1. Tenant Scope, applies to all resources within the tenant. An identity with tenant scope has the highest level of access across all resources in the tenant. This is the highest tier of oversight and will typically have roles with "administrator" in the title. A global administrator is assigned when a person signs up for the Azure AD organization. A global administrator cannot remove themselves from their own assignment as this could potentially leave the subscription with no administrator.

2. Management Group, involves groupings or boxes that govern different subscriptions. There can be many levels of Management groups stacked in a hierarchical tree-like structure. Management groups enable you to enforce rules and policies across a number of subscriptions.

3. Subscription Scope, applies to all resources within a subscription. An identity with a subscription scope can access all resources within that subscription but not across subscriptions.

4. Resource Group Scope, applies to all the sources within a resource group. An identity with a resource group scope can access the resources within that group but not across resource groups. A groups administrator sits at this level and issues full capabilities to create, delete, update, and manage group membership but cannot create, manage, or update user accounts.

5. Resource Scope, applies to a specific resource within a resource group. An identity with resource scope has access to a specific resource only. 

